            <p><strong><a href="http://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2016/10/us-renews-fight-for-the-right-to-seize-content-from-the-worlds-servers/" target="_blank">US Renews Fight for the Right to Seize Content from the World’s Servers</a></strong></p>
            <p>Federal prosecutors have asked the U.S. Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit to reconsider a July 2016 decision by a three-judge panel finding that while federal law permits U.S. authorities to seize information on U.S.-based servers, it does not allow access to content on foreign servers. Closely watched by many in the privacy community, the media, and the business world, this case could potentially move up to the U.S. Supreme Court if the appellate court declines to reconsider its prior ruling.</p>
